According to a report by Intel Market Research, the global Long-Duration Energy Storage (LDES) Market was valued at USD 1.9 billion in 2025 and is projected to grow from USD 2.1 billion in 2026 to USD 4.7 billion by 2034, expanding at a CAGR of 9.6% during the forecast period. The market is witnessing strong momentum as governments, utilities, and private enterprises accelerate investments in renewable energy infrastructure and grid modernization. Long-duration energy storage technologies, capable of storing electricity for eight hours or more, are becoming essential for balancing intermittent renewable energy sources such as wind and solar while ensuring reliable, resilient, and low-carbon power systems. Favorable policy incentives, increasing clean energy commitments, technological advancements, and growing utility-scale deployments are collectively driving the global adoption of long-duration storage solutions.
